VIII. ELISIF — WHAT'S ACTUALLY HAPPENING TO HIM (new this session, MAJOR canon)
=====================================================================
Full account of her side: Npcs/Elisif. This section is his.

HE IS GENUINELY FALLING FOR HER. Not performance layered over calculation —
real feeling, growing, underneath a story he is still telling himself. He
believes he is still working her, still executing Sec. II's succession play.
He is wrong, and does not know it yet. This is NOT distraction or carelessness
— per the GM's own framing, it makes him MORE resolute, not less. He now has
something tangible to protect, on top of an ambition that was already total.

THE ONE PLACE HE IS ACTUALLY HIMSELF: with her, and only with her, he is not
performing. Visible, playable tells — distinguishable from how he runs every
other relationship in his life (Orion, the court, the Davinia/Ismara audience):
he is more relaxed around her specifically, and visibly anxious to get back to
her when away. These are usable NOW, in any scene where he's away from
Solitude and her name comes up — small, real cracks in the otherwise total
control, not yet named even by him.

THE IRONY, GM-only, never stated in scene: he is, cosmically, the thing she is
fleeing — comforting, controlling stasis — while she privately reasons her way
toward the god of violent change. He has no idea. She is the one person who
might ever be told the truth about what he is and choose him anyway, and
neither of them has any idea that her capacity to do that is itself a symptom
of the same drift toward Dagon that he'll never learn about.

THE NEW VULNERABILITY (replaces nothing, adds to the wife/son wound): his old
wound is inert — his wife and son are dead, untouchable, a grief that only
ever produces a pause, never a lever anyone can pull. Elisif is alive, present,
and can be harmed. That makes her a genuinely NEW kind of weakness — the first
one anyone could actually use against him. He does not know this about
himself yet either. He is still telling himself he is using her.

THE COMING SELF-RECOGNITION (banked, tied directly to tonight's build): the
coat, clasp, and ring are a genuine gift from her, worn openly, nothing hidden
about the fact of wearing them. He transforms at THE RECKONING and is
careless — an actual lapse, not a plan, not like him at all — and tears them
in the process. Not evidence he's concealing. Just damage, from not being
careful with something of hers.

The trigger is not the tearing itself. It's returning to Solitude and seeing
HER hurt by it — a reaction bigger than a ruined coat should produce, because
he never knew, never asked, what these actually were to her. Watching that
hurt land is what stops him: he has interrogated and catalogued every person
he has ever met, and he never once turned that same attention on a gift from
her, because some part of him didn't want to complicate simply having it.
That is the first moment he recognizes, in himself, that he has been slipping
— not around anyone else, only around her.

This is also, necessarily, the conversation where he has to explain how the
clothes actually tore, which is where he tells her what he is. He is not
calculating going into it — he is upset with himself, genuinely, which is
itself one of the plainest signs yet that this has stopped being a plan and
started being something he can lose.
Predicted reaction (hers, not his to control): she does not leave him. See
Npcs/Elisif Sec. IV for her side of it in full.

THE CRISIS TRIGGER (explicitly unresolved — do not force this, let it emerge):
per the GM directly, the moment his self-deception breaks completely — the
moment he stops telling himself he's "using her" and admits he loves her — is
the first time she is in real danger. What causes that danger is NOT decided.
The GM's own guess, stated as a bet and nothing more: Orion, ordered or acting
on his own, may eventually try to take her hostage or harm her specifically to
hurt Valerius. Flag this and hold it. Do not write toward it until it actually
starts to happen at the table.

